message.content: "cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.NE". The paper deals with self-supervised learning of video representations using convolutional neural networks, which is a common topic in computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) research. The odd-one-out learning technique proposed in the paper involves identifying the unrelated or odd element from a set of otherwise related elements, which is a form of anomaly detection and could be classified under artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of video data and action recognition tasks also suggests a potential fit with multimedia (cs.MM) research. Finally, the end-to-end learning approach and use of neural networks could also be relevant to neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
